

=Description=

Richard Davis Hames:

"Wayfinding refers to the ancient knowledge tradition that enabled Micronesians to travel vast distances on the open ocean. Using finely-tuned
observations of the stars, the sun, the clouds, the ocean swells, and other signs of nature for clues to direction and location of a vessel at sea,
these master navigators were voyaging with pinpoint accuracy for thousands of years before the invention of European navigational instruments. By continuously monitoring the environment they knew where they were, relative to where they had come from. Wayfinders held
their vessels to be fixed points on a star compass - the art and science of wayfinding enshrined in their ability to visualise a destination until it
materialized on the horizon. These mental constructs ensured they did not get lost."

